# Shared AI Context

This file is the shared adapter between Claude Code and Codex for this workspace. Treat it as the
stable entry point for user preferences, memory locations, skill mappings, and cross-tool fallbacks.
Claude Code does not read this file automatically (it reads `CLAUDE.md`) — it's Codex's entry point,
reached via the root `AGENTS.md`.

## Load Order

1. Read this file first.
2. Read the workspace `CLAUDE.md` for repo overview and conventions.
3. If working inside a repo subfolder, read that repo's local `AGENTS.md` and/or `CLAUDE.md`.
4. Read task-specific memory only when the task touches that area.

Do not copy secrets from `~/.claude` or other Claude state into project files. If a helper already
embeds credentials, reference the helper path instead of duplicating the credential.

## User Preferences

- Respond in Spanish by default. Keep technical terms in English when that is the natural term in the codebase.
- Be concise. Do not repeat prior context. Explain only when it changes the decision, risk, or next step.
- Never add a "Co-Authored-By" line to commits — only the user is the author.
- After any change under `CloudHubCorp/Backoffice/`, run `make build` before considering the work done — the Astro Backoffice needs compiling for changes to take effect.

## Workspace Memory

Shared memory for this workspace lives at:

`.ai-memory/` (workspace root, next to `CLAUDE.md` — not per-repo)

Files the `/dev-*` skills read and write:

- `.ai-memory/user_profile.json` — communication/workflow preferences, loaded by `/dev` at the start of every ticket.
- `.ai-memory/epics.json` — cached `${PROJECT_KEY}` epic list, maintained by `/dev-create` so epics aren't re-queried every session.
- `.ai-memory/snapshots/<TICKET>.json` — checkpoints written by `/dev-reflect`, read by `/dev`, `/dev-resume`, `/dev-status`.
- `.ai-memory/assessments/<TICKET>.json` — technical assessments written by `/dev-assess`.
- `.ai-memory/vps-config.json` — production VPS connection settings for `/dev-db-sync`.
- `.ai-memory/review_rounds/<TICKET>.json` — PR review history written by `/dev-pr`.
- `.ai-memory/db-backups/` — downloaded DB snapshots from `/dev-db-sync`.
- `.ai-memory/patterns.json`, `.ai-memory/decisions.json`, `.ai-memory/mistakes.json`, `.ai-memory/global_rules.json` — cross-ticket learnings written by `/dev-reflect`.

Memory writes are part of the shared workflow — both agents may update `.ai-memory/` files directly as
local memory persistence. Ask before Jira transitions or Jira comments unless the user explicitly
requested the flow that includes them (e.g. `/dev-reflect` closing mode, `/dev-assess`).

Imported Claude project memory index (legacy — prefer `.ai-memory/` for new learnings unless the user
explicitly asks to update Claude memory):

`${CLAUDE_MEMORY_INDEX}`

## Shared Skill Adapter

Canonical skill sources live in `.ai/skills/`. Claude Code discovers them automatically via symlinks
at `.claude/skills/<name>` → `../../.ai/skills/<name>` — no extra Claude-side config needed. Codex has
no reliable equivalent auto-discovery, so this file is the resolution path: when the user's intent
matches one of the rows below, read the corresponding `.ai/skills/<name>/SKILL.md` directly and execute
that workflow with the user's arguments as `$ARGUMENTS`.

| User intent | Skill source |
| --- | --- |
| Full ticket workflow (branch, develop, validate, commit, push) | `.ai/skills/dev/SKILL.md` |
| New idea/requirement with no ticket yet — spec + file a Jira ticket | `.ai/skills/dev-create/SKILL.md` |
| Technical deep dive / assessment before coding | `.ai/skills/dev-assess/SKILL.md` |
| Create a PR or handle review comments | `.ai/skills/dev-pr/SKILL.md` |
| Snapshot / closing reflection, persist learnings | `.ai/skills/dev-reflect/SKILL.md` |
| Resume a ticket already in progress | `.ai/skills/dev-resume/SKILL.md` |
| Review a teammate's PR ("review <PR URL>") | `.ai/skills/dev-review/SKILL.md` |
| DB migration workflow (QuintaApp-Api) | `.ai/skills/dev-migration/SKILL.md` |
| Read-only ticket/workspace status | `.ai/skills/dev-status/SKILL.md` |
| Pull a production DB snapshot | `.ai/skills/dev-db-sync/SKILL.md` |

`.ai/skills/dev/SKILL.md` is the orchestrator: when a request doesn't clearly match one of the other
rows, start there — it routes to the rest via its own dispatch table.

### Command Resolution Rules

- Do not treat `/dev-*` as a literal Codex slash command. Resolve it as: read the matching
  `.ai/skills/<name>/SKILL.md` and execute that workflow with the given arguments.
- When one skill delegates to another (e.g. `/dev` → `/dev-assess`), stop the current phase and follow
  the delegated skill's file first, exactly as it says.
- `$ARGUMENTS` in a skill file means the arguments supplied by the user or by the parent skill's delegation.
- Claude UI mechanics have Codex fallbacks:
  - `/rename ...`: no-op in Codex; keep the intended title in the working summary if useful.
  - `Task(...)` / subagent delegation: do the work locally unless the user explicitly asks for parallel delegation.
  - `/ultrareview`: perform a normal Codex code-review pass focused on bugs, regressions, security, and tests instead.

Preserve every safety gate written into the skill files: ask before destructive operations, before
pushes, before Jira transitions/comments, and before any other external state change — unless the user
has already authorized it in the current conversation.

## Jira

Use the scripts instead of duplicating Jira credentials:

`uv run ${JIRA_SCRIPTS}/<core|workflow>/<script>.py <command> ...`

Common commands:

- `core/jira-issue.py get <ISSUE_KEY> --json`
- `core/jira-search.py query "<JQL>" --json`
- `workflow/jira-comment.py add <ISSUE_KEY> "<text>"`
- `workflow/jira-transition.py do <ISSUE_KEY> "<transition>"`
- `workflow/jira-create.py issue <PROJECT_KEY> "<summary>" -t <type> -d "<description>" --parent <EPIC_KEY>`

Jira base URL: `${JIRA_BASE_URL}`. Project key: `${PROJECT_KEY}`.

## Workspace Working Rules

- This workspace contains multiple repos: `${REPOS}`. Determine the affected repo(s) before editing — see `CLAUDE.md` for the full architecture map.
- Repos matching `${SPECIAL_REPO_PATTERNS}` use `${SPECIAL_REPO_BASE}` as their base branch; everything else uses `master`.
- `/dev-db-sync` is only configured for: `${DB_SYNC_REPOS}` (empty means disabled).

## Updating This Adapter

If a future session discovers a new recurring rule that should affect both Claude and Codex, add it
here. Ticket-specific details belong in `.ai-memory/tickets/` or `.ai-memory/snapshots/`, not here.
